/*
 * What to commit:
 *
 * DO commit:
 * - Source files (src/)
 * - Configuration files (webpack.config.js, tailwind.config.js, etc.)
 * - package.json
 * - README.md
 * - .gitignore
 *
 * DO NOT commit:
 * - node_modules/ (dependencies)
 * - dist/ or build/ (build output)
 * - .env files (environment variables with secrets)
 * - Editor/IDE settings (.vscode/, .idea/)
 * - Log files
 * - Cache directories
 *
 *
 * Project Structure Example:
 *
 * project/
 * ├── src/                 # Source files (COMMIT)
 * │   ├── index.js
 * │   ├── styles.css
 * │   └── components/
 * ├── dist/                # Build output (IGNORE)
 * ├── node_modules/        # Dependencies (IGNORE)
 * ├── webpack.config.js    # Config (COMMIT)
 * ├── tailwind.config.js   # Config (COMMIT)
 * ├── package.json         # Dependencies list (COMMIT)
 * ├── .gitignore           # This file (COMMIT)
 * └── README.md            # Documentation (COMMIT)
 *
 *
 * Usage:
 *
 * 1. Copy this file to project root as .gitignore
 * 2. Review and uncomment sections as needed
 * 3. Add project-specific ignores
 * 4. Commit: git add .gitignore && git commit -m "Add gitignore"
 *
 *
 * Common Customizations:
 *
 * # Commit source maps for debugging
 * Remove: # *.map
 *
 * # Ignore specific build output directories
 * Add: /public/assets/
 * Add: /static/dist/
 *
 * # Keep package-lock.json for consistent installs
 * Remove: package-lock.json
 *
 * # Project-specific files
 * Add: /uploads/
 * Add: /data/*.csv
 *
 *
 * Verification:
 *
 * # Check what would be ignored
 * git status --ignored
 *
 * # Check if specific file is ignored
 * git check-ignore -v filename
 *
 * # Remove already-tracked files from git
 * git rm -r --cached node_modules
 * git rm --cached .env
 */
